title: For Sale:  Citadel Government 1911 custom with tons of accessories/ammo
postcontent:
Up for sale/trade is my Citadel 1911. I am sad to let it go but I am consolidating handgun calibers and 45ACP will not be the winner of this. This gun is, by far, the best handgun I've ever shot. I have not shot expensive 1911s, but I have shot most other plastic handguns and this beats them all. It has surprised me, as a mediocre shooter, how much better I am with this in my hand. Enough being sentimental...

The Citadel Government 1911 has a parkerized finish with a 5" barrel, full length guide rod, ambidextrous safety, Novak-cut dovetail for front and rear sights, skeletonized trigger, extended beavertail and flared ejection port. I'm sure there's some stuff I'm missing, but this 1911 comes with all the bells and whistles from Armscor (RIA), built for Legacy Sports/Howa/Puma under the Citadel name.

What's included:
- Novak front tritium sight (white)
- Wilson Combat extended magazine release
- Wilson Combat flat mainspring housing
- Rob Bonacci trigger job
- Polished feed ramp
- 3x blued Chip McCormick Shooting Star 8-round magazines with base pads
- VZ-style black G10 diamondback grips OR Wilson Combat rosewood double diamond grips
- Original box, grips, parts, paperwork, lock, barrel bushing tool

I used this gun to compete in 3 IDPA matches this year. It shot flawlessly except for Wolf steel. At this point I brought it to Rob and he polished and shaped the feed ramps perfectly. It feeds hollow points, brass FMJ, steel FMJ...it will feed empty cases if you wanted to. Gun is in excellent mechanical condition and very good cosmetic condition with minor holster wear, and some finish wear by the trigger and safety (no idiot mark). The trigger pull is light with an obvious and crisp breaking point, and no overtravel.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Victory
postcontent:
This is a Smith & Wesson Victory Model 38 cal revolver.

Victories were produced for the "Lend Lease" program during WWII and shipped to Australia, New Zealand, Britain and other allied countries as well as to defense contractors in the US for security personnel.

This particular revolver was produced in late 1943 or early 1944 and has been refinished in nickel with white grips.

Here are the markings;

Bottom of barrel; V2679xx
Left side of barrel; Smith & Wesson
Right side of bbl; 38 S&W CTG then a different stamp, looks like it was added later; SPECIAL
Above the trigger guard on right side; Made in USA
Right side plate; S&W logo stamp
Bottom of butt; V2679xx
Rear of cylinder; V2679xx
Crane; N 21359 21359
There are no other marks, proof marks or US Property marks.

The nickel is OK, some minor scratches but on the right side it looks like road rash. The cylinder has some deep scratches and the end of the barrel has some as well. The lanyard ring hole on the butt is apparant where it was filled before refinish.

The timing seems good, the lock up is tight and the trigger is wonderful(it is a S&W after all).

It is an easy to shoot quality S&W revolver and would make a great inexpensive home defense weapon for the person who wants something less complicated than a semi-auto. And it has some historical significance.

The Mosin-Nagant rifle was adopted by Russia in 1891 after trials of several repeating bolt actions. It fires the 7.62x54r cartridge and is a combination of designs by Russian Sergei Mosin and Belgian Leon Nagant whose primary contribution was the feed system. The official designation is “3 line rifle, model 1891”. A “line” is a unit of measure equal to 1/10th of an inch. Production of the Model 1891 took place at the Russian arsenals at Izhevsk, Tula, and Sestroryetsk. title: For Sale:  Armalite AR10 Carbine with Rainer Arms UltrMatch barrel and extras
postcontent:
I have this AR10 carbine. It started out as an Armalite AR10A4 carbine. The base price for this carbine is $1300. I used the original lightweight barrel last hunting season and took a buck out in Arizona. The carbine had about 100 rounds through it that year. I changed the barrel after hunting season to a Rainer Arms Ultramatch ($400). It’s more of a medium contour and groups nicely. I’ve only put about 20 rounds through the new barrel and used it to take 2x does this year. It also sports a Daniel’s Defense 9.0 AR10 FF rail ($350). I’ve changed the buffer tube out to a standard AR15 carbine tube and added a buffer and spring from Slash’s Heavy Buffers ($135). It’s an XH buffer. It enables one to use the shorter AR15 buffer tube (for more flexibility in choosing a stock) and reduces recoil while increasing reliability. There have been zero stoppages to date. The stock is a VLTOR Emod which in my opinion gives the best cheek weld and length of pull for a scope carbine. It also balances the mid-weight barrel nicely. The scope is a Leupold Mk IV 1.5-5x20mm MR/T with SPR recticle and M2 knobs. It’s mounted in a Larue LT104-30 with throw levers. The package is $1,080 from Larue.
If you do the math, it that comes to $3265 not including the labor, stock, and included Daniels’ Defense sling mount. It’s a great shooter that will hold 1 MOA or less with good ammo. It’s a great balance between weight, length, and precision capability. The tube is barely used and still has thousands of rounds left.

I am asking $3000. I don’t need to sell it, but I am thinking of going a different direction on another project. 

Serious inquiries only.
